Observations from Exploratory Data Analysis¶

There are 93,142 logins. I did not find any issues with data. Pandas could intrinsically convert datatype to DateTime type without producing any null, which indicates that data is formatted well. We have the login data for a period of ~3.5 months from 1970-01-01 20:12:16 to 1970-04-13 18:57:38. There are some duplicate login times, but this is entirely possible as more than one user can login at the same time. I grouped the time stamp at 15 minutes interval and counted the number of logins at this interval over the period of entire day. We can see two peaks in the number of logins. One is between 10 PM 5 AM and another is somewhere between 11 AM 1 PM. This may have something to do with complementary circadian rhythms of neighboring cities of Gotham and Metropolis. The login counts were minimum between 6 AM 9 AM. When I plot the login counts over the dates, I found a perfect cyclical patterns occurring at an interval of about 5 days. Therefore, I plot the login counts over the day of week. It is interesting that login count is minimum on Monday and then it increases reaching its peak on Saturday. On Sunday also the number of logins were almost the same as Saturday. It appears that the highest logins were seen on weekends.

Experiment and metrics design¶

A toll bridge, with a two-way toll, between Gotham and Metropolis is main factor that discourages driver partners taking intercity trip. The proposed experiment is aimed at encouraging driver partners to take intercity trips by reimbursing all toll costs.

So to measure the success of proposed experiment, I will track how toll reimbursement changes the proportion of intercity trips in a specified period.

Proportion of intercity trips = Number of intercity trips/Total number of trips

If a driver picks a customer at Gotham, drops off in Metropolis, and then picks another customer in Metropolis and drops off at Gotham, this should be considered as 2 intercity trips. However, if driver go back to Gotham empty, this should be considered as 1 intercity trip. I think this information is easily available in the trip details that is being collected. I also assume that ultimate inc. collect trip-wise detail like pick up point and destination point. This can be used to determine whether a trip is intercity trip (1) or not (0).

Setting up the experiment, statistical test and interpreting the results

To set up the experiment, I need some information from Ultimatum Inc. Since this information is not available, I will assume few things.

  1. Historically, what is the total number of daily trips and what fraction of these trips is intercity trips. Let me assume that over the past year average daily total trips is 1000 trips and on average 10% of these trips are intercity trips.
  2. What % increase in intercity trips will be of practical significance. Let me assume that 1% increase in intercity trips is of practical significance. This is determined based on cost of implementing the toll imbursement and benefit obtained from increase in intercity trips.

My control will be no toll reimbursement. Treatment will be toll imbursement.

Null hypothesis (Ho): % intercity trips when there is toll reimbursement = % intercity trips when there is no toll reimbursement

Alternate hypothesis (H1): % intercity trips when there is toll reimbursement > % intercity trips when there is no toll reimbursement

I can obtain % intercity trips when there is no toll reimbursement from historical data, which is assumed to be 10%. But to control for all extraneous factors, it is a good idea to run both control and treatment almost at the same time. One possibility is to reimburse toll only on alternate day (e.g., On Monday there will be toll reimbursement, Tuesday no reimbursement, Wednesday there will reimbursement so on). We should send notifications to driver in advance and at every day during experiment to inform them what day there will be toll reimbursement and on what day there will be no toll reimbursement.

Next thing is to determine how many days we need to run this experiment. This depends on statistical power we want and standard deviation of the variable. Let me assume that we want 80% power. This means that, if there is indeed 1% increase in intercity trips because of toll reimbursement, we should have a 80% chance of detecting it (80% chance of rejecting null hypothesis).

So, we can use alpha = 5%, Beta (power) = 80%, standard deviation = sqrt(p(1-p) = sqrt(0.1 * 0.9) = 0.3 to calculate minimum number of samples (trips) required for this experiment. This estimation is important since running this experiment could cost a lot of money for Ultimate as they have to reimburse toll.

Number of samples (per group) can be calculated using this formula.

0.01 (practical significance) = 2.8 * SE (standard error)

0.01 = 2.8 * sqrt(0.32/n + 0.32/n)

n = 14,112

So, we need 14,112 x 2 = ~28,000 trips for this experiment. Considering historical average of 1000 trips/day, we need to run this experiment for 28 days. On 14 alternate days we reimburse toll and another 14 days we dont. The number of trips may not be same during all days historically. We need to account for this so that eventually in both groups we get more or less same number of trips.

Then we can calculate % of intercity trips during tolled and toll-free (toll reimubrsed) days.

Then we can use two sample Z-test (sample size is much larger than 30) to test hypothesis. If the % intercity trips increased more than 1% in treatment, and if it is statistically significant, then we can permanently implement this proposal of reimbursing toll.

Determining whether a user is active in their 6th month¶

Suppose a user sign up on Jan 1st, on June 1st, the user will be into his 6th month. A user is considered to be retained if they were active (i.e. took a trip) in the preceding 30 days on any particular date. So if this user book a trip any day on or after May 2nd, he will be considered active.

So, I will add up 5 months to sign up date and then subtract 30 days to get a cut-off date. If the last_trip for the user is on or after this cut-off date, the user will be labelled as 1 (active) and 0 (inactive) otherwise.

In [68]:
retention_df['cutoff_date'] = retention_df['signup_date'] + pd.Timedelta(5, unit='M') - pd.Timedelta(31, unit='D')
# Subtracted 31 days, instead of 30 days, because when I add 5 months to Jan 1st, it becomes June 2
# I used calendar month to calculate 6th month, 
# as when we say 6th month, we generally refer to calendar month, not 30 days month

retention_df['is_active'] = (retention_df['last_trip_date'] >= retention_df['cutoff_date']).astype('int')

Characterstics of the dataset¶

There are 50,000 records in this dataset. The target label (whether an user is active in his/her 6th month or not) is little imbalanced. 55% of the users are inactive. There are some missing values in the columns avg_rating_of_driver, phone, avg_rating_by_driver. More than 68% of the users seem to be using iPhone app. I did not find a significant correlation among features except between avg_surge and surge_pct, which have a correlation of 0.8.

Handling missing values¶

Impute missing value with mean (numerical variable) or mode (categorical variable) of the feature

In [73]:
# Fill na with mean (numerical variable) or mode (categorical variable)
retention_df['avg_rating_of_driver'] = (retention_df['avg_rating_of_driver']
                                        .fillna(retention_df['avg_rating_of_driver'].mean()))
retention_df['avg_rating_by_driver'] = (retention_df['avg_rating_by_driver']
                                        .fillna(retention_df['avg_rating_by_driver'].mean()))
retention_df['phone'] = (retention_df['phone']
                                        .fillna(retention_df['phone'].mode()[0]))

Which features to use in model training¶

We definitely need to remove sign_up date and last_trip date as if we include these variables, we are going to encode target variables in the feature itself. There is a strong correlation (0.8) between avg_surge and surge_pct. So, it is a good idea to remove one of these variables. Since surge_pct has slightly higher correlation with the target variable, I will remove avg_surge. It should be noted that the target variable does not seem to have a strong correlation with any of the predictors. Let us see how our model is going perform.

In [75]:
# Prepare features and target variables
features = retention_df.drop(['is_active', 'signup_date', 'last_trip_date', 'avg_surge', 'cutoff_date'], axis=1)
target = retention_df['is_active']

XGBoost¶

XGBoost is an ensemble method that is known to perform well on many datasets. Boosting sequentially converts weak learners into strong learners by correcting the classification errors of previous weak learner in the sequence. Since XGBoost intrinsically handle class imbalance, it is useful in this case as there is a slight class imbalance. As it is a tree based method, feature scaling is not necessary. Furthermore, this algorithm is optimized for parallel computing, so that I can use multi cores for training.

In [79]:
from xgboost import XGBClassifier
# XGBoost with tuned hyperparameters
clf = XGBClassifier(random_state=42)

Cross validation¶

In [80]:
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.metrics import f1_score, make_scorer, accuracy_score, classification_report
# XGBoost with tuned hyperparameters
clf = XGBClassifier(random_state=42)

params = {'max_depth': [3, 5, 10], 
              'n_estimators' : [100, 200]}

# Make an f1_score scoring object.
# Since classes are imbalanced, I used f1_score. But tried accuracy also and gave almost the same result
scorer = make_scorer(f1_score)

# Perform grid search on the classifier using 'scorer' as the scoring method.
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(clf, params, scoring=scorer)

        
# Fit the grid search object to the training data and find the optimal parameters.
grid_fit = grid_obj.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Get the estimator.
clf = grid_fit.best_estimator_

# Fit the new model.
clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Print best parmeters
print(f"Best parameters: {grid_fit.best_params_}")

test_predictions = clf.predict(X_test)

test_accuracy = round(accuracy_score(y_test, test_predictions), 2)
test_f1 = round(f1_score(y_test, test_predictions), 2)

print (f'Test accuracy: {test_accuracy}')
print (f'Test f1: {test_f1}')

Conclusion¶

I bulild a XGBoost model to predict whether an user will be active in his/her 6th month. This model has an accuracy of 78% and f1 score of 73%. This is significant improvement over benchmark Naive Bayes model, which has an accuracy of 68% and f1 score of 65%. This model can be used by Ultimate Inc. to predict customer churn. They can offer some discounts to the customers who are not likely to be retained.
